      "body": "The dataset is clear. Here's what I found and the research questions I'll pursue:\n\n---\n\n## \ud83d\udcc1 Inventory\n**1 file:** `online_vs_offline_learning_dataset.csv`  \n- **1,000 rows \u00d7 6 columns**: `Learning_Mode`, `Subject`, `Study_Hours`, `Retention_Score`, `Focus_Level`, `Exam_Score`\n- Perfectly balanced: 500 Online / 500 Offline students across 5 subjects\n\n---\n\n## \ud83d\udd2c Proposed Research Questions\n\n1. **Does learning mode (online vs. offline) significantly affect exam performance, retention, and focus?** \u2014 Compare group means and distributions across the two modes.\n\n2. **What are the strongest predictors of Exam Score?** \u2014 Retention Score and Focus Level both correlate strongly (r=0.80 and r=0.52); does learning mode moderate these relationships?\n\n3. **Do online and offline learners differ in subject-specific performance?** \u2014 Are certain subjects better suited to one mode over the other?\n\n---\n\nI'll pursue all three questions. Proceeding with full analysis, visualizations, Jupyter notebook, and LaTeX paper now.Now generating the Jupyter notebook and LaTeX paper in parallel.Now let me show the generated figures inline:---\n\n## \u2705 Complete Analysis Delivered\n\nAll six phases are done. Here's the full report:\n\n---\n\n## Research Questions\n\n| # | Question | Answer |\n|---|---|---|\n| RQ1 | Does learning mode affect Exam Score and Retention Score? | **Yes, significantly.** Offline > Online for both (p < 0.001) |\n| RQ2 | Do Focus Level and Study Hours vary by mode? | **No.** Both differences are non-significant (p > 0.29) |\n| RQ3 | What predicts Exam Score, and does mode moderate it? | **Retention dominates** (r \u2248 0.80 in both modes); Focus is moderate (r = 0.48\u20130.56); Study Hours is negligible |\n\n---\n\n## Key Findings\n\n### 1. Offline learners outperform online learners\n| Metric | Online | Offline | p-value |\n|--------|--------|---------|---------|\n| Exam Score | 70.21 \u00b1 12.79 | **73.14 \u00b1 13.03** | 0.0004 *** |\n| Retention Score | 70.66 \u00b1 17.88 | **74.72 \u00b1 17.29** | 0.0003 *** |\n| Focus Level | 70.72 \u00b1 18.18 | 71.80 \u00b1 17.93 | 0.347 ns |\n| Study Hours | 4.50 \u00b1 2.05 | 4.63 \u00b1 1.95 | 0.299 ns |\n\n### 2. Retention Score is the strongest predictor of Exam Score (~r = 0.80 in both modes) \u2014 far stronger than Focus Level or Study Hours\n\n### 3. Offline advantage is consistent across all 5 subjects \u2014 largest in **History** (4.09 pt gap), smallest in **Math** (1.49 pt gap)\n\n---\n\n## Generated Output Files\n\nAll files saved to `~/Desktop/online_learning/output/`:\n\n| File | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `analysis.py` | Statistical analysis script |\n| `fig1_score_distributions.pdf/.png` | Box plots: Exam, Retention, Focus by mode |\n| `fig2_exam_by_subject.pdf/.png` | Grouped bar chart by subject \u00d7 mode |\n| `fig3_retention_vs_exam.pdf/.png` | Retention vs. Exam scatter with regression |\n| `fig4_focus_vs_exam.pdf/.png` | Focus vs. Exam scatter with regression |\n| `fig5_study_hours_distribution.pdf/.png` | Study hours KDE by mode |\n| `fig6_subject_heatmap.pdf/.png` | Heatmap: subject \u00d7 mode mean exam score |\n| `research_notebook.ipynb` | Reproducible Jupyter notebook (22 cells) |\n| `research_notebook_executed.ipynb` | Executed notebook with all outputs |\n| `paper.tex` | Full LaTeX paper source |\n| `paper.pdf` | Compiled 9-page academic paper |"
    }
  ],
